parse_intent self-test + investigation
date: 2026-04-19T04:00:00Z
device: Huawei P20 Lite (ANE-LX1) via adb, 8 threads
model: tinyllama.gguf (Q4_0) via llama-cli b1-3f7c29d, grammar-constrained JSON
script: demo/parse_intent.py

---- 8-phrase self-test, TinyLlama Q4_0 + schema grammar (--temp 0 --top-k 1) ----

[19.7 s]  "lean left"                               -> {"c":"pose","n":"lean_left","d":1500}   CORRECT
[24.9 s]  "could you lean to the left please"       -> {"c":"pose","n":"lean_left","d":1500}   CORRECT
[24.7 s]  "bow down a little"                       -> {"c":"pose","n":"bow_front","d":1800}   CORRECT
[25.4 s]  "walk forward now"                        -> {"c":"walk","on":true,"stride":150,"step":400}   CORRECT
[27.5 s]  "stop what you are doing"                 -> {"c":"pose","n":"lean_left","d":1500}   WRONG  (expected stop)
[27.0 s]  "jump"                                    -> {"c":"pose","n":"lean_left","d":1500}   WRONG  (expected jump)
[27.2 s]  "tell me a joke"                          -> {"c":"pose","n":"lean_left","d":1500}   WRONG  (expected noop)
[27.1 s]  "turn around"                             -> {"c":"pose","n":"lean_left","d":1500}   WRONG  (expected noop)

Score: 4 / 8.  Every failure collapsed to the first schema option (pose/lean_left).

---- why this fails ----

TinyLlama Q4_0 + grammar-constrained decoding + --temp 0 --top-k 1 is deterministic:
at each step the single highest-probability allowed token wins.  For weakly-signalled
inputs (single-word commands like "jump", or out-of-vocab inputs like "tell me a
joke") the logits on the first content token favor "pose" over "stop"/"jump"/"noop"
because the few-shot prompt has more pose examples.  Once "pose" is emitted, the
grammar + logits lock in the first enum value ("lean_left").  The grammar constraint
ensures syntactic validity but cannot recover from a semantic error in the first
token.

---- follow-up: Gemma 3 1B ----

Tried same prompt with gemma3.gguf on phone.  llama-cli on this build drops into
interactive REPL mode for Gemma regardless of -st/--simple-io combinations
(banner prints but no generation reaches stdout in the 40-token budget).  Not a
quick drop-in; would need either a different CLI build, a non-interactive chat
template flag, or a different invocation pattern.  Punted.

---- follow-up: TinyLlama without the grammar constraint ----

Ran the same prompt with --temp 0 --top-k 1 but no -jf schema.json.  TinyLlama
stopped producing JSON at all — it responded with "To map the user robot command
'jump' to ONE wire command JSON, follow these steps: 1. Find the 'c'..." on every
failing case.  Classic small-model failure mode: without the grammar scaffold,
Q4_0 drifts into meta-explanation instead of emitting the answer.

---- conclusion ----

parse_intent.py is usable for naturally-phrased 4+ word commands that pattern-match
the few-shot examples.  It is NOT usable as the daemon's primary intent stage
because single-word commands and out-of-vocab inputs collapse to pose/lean_left.

The keyword matcher in demo/robot_daemon.py handles all 14 tested phrases correctly
(including these 8) with a ~0 ms regex match.  That is the default path.

parse_intent.py stays in the repo behind the robot_daemon --with-llm flag for two
reasons:
  (a) documents the exact failure mode so we don't repeat this experiment,
  (b) gives us a ready-to-run scaffold for when we swap in Gemma 3 1B
      (fix the REPL issue) or a bigger instruction-tuned model.

---- integration check ----

  $ python3 demo/robot_daemon.py --mode text --dry-run --no-tts
  # all 14 test phrases, including the 4 that break TinyLlama, classify correctly
  # in < 1 ms via the regex matcher.  log at /tmp/robot-test.log.

---- Gemma 3 1B re-test ----
date: 2026-04-19T<later>Z
device: Huawei P20 Lite (ANE-LX1) serial 9WV4C18C11005454
model: /data/local/tmp/gemma3.gguf (720 MB) via llama-cli b1-3f7c29d
flags: -st --simple-io --log-disable --no-perf --temp 0 --top-k 1 -jf schema.json < /dev/null

Flag catalog (what did / did not bypass interactive mode on this build):

  -no-cnv alone                 FAIL: llama-cli still prints the ">" REPL prompt and
                                blocks on stdin.  Output is just a stream of ">" lines
                                until -n budget exhausted, no generation.
  -no-cnv --simple-io           FAIL: same as above.
  -no-cnv < /dev/null           FAIL: same ">" spam.  Confirms -no-cnv is not the
                                right switch on this build when the model ships
                                with a chat template (Gemma does).
  -st  (single-turn)            WORKS for Gemma: banner + prompt echo + one JSON
                                response + "Exiting..." and clean exit.  This is
                                the same flag that works for TinyLlama.
  -st --simple-io --log-disable WORKS; cleaner output (no ANSI colour, no
                                verbose timing).  Selected.

Winning invocation:

  ./llama-cli -m gemma3.gguf -p '<prompt>' -n 64 -t 8 --no-warmup \
              -st --simple-io --log-disable --no-perf --temp 0 --top-k 1 \
              -jf schema.json < /dev/null

8-phrase re-test (--temp 0 --top-k 1, schema grammar, n_predict=64):

  [42.32 s] "lean left"                         -> {"c":"pose","n":"lean_left","d":1500}    CORRECT
  [62.06 s] "could you lean to the left please" -> {"c":"pose","n":"lean_left","d":1500}    CORRECT
  [38.01 s] "bow down a little"                 -> {"c":"pose","n":"bow_front","d":500}     CORRECT*
  [44.59 s] "walk forward now"                  -> {"c":"walk","on":true,"stride":150,"step":400}  CORRECT
  [25.55 s] "stop what you are doing"           -> {"c":"stop"}                             CORRECT (TinyLlama: WRONG)
  [24.13 s] "jump"                              -> {"c":"jump"}                             CORRECT (TinyLlama: WRONG)
  [25.23 s] "tell me a joke"                    -> {"c":"stop"}                             WRONG   (TinyLlama: WRONG)
  [25.13 s] "turn around"                       -> {"c":"noop"}                             CORRECT (TinyLlama: WRONG)

  * bow_front duration is 500 instead of the canonical 1800, but canonicalize()
    rewrites it to {"c":"pose","n":"bow_front","d":1800} which is the correct
    wire command.

Score: 7 / 8.  vs TinyLlama: 4 / 8.  Gemma correctly recovers all four single-
word / out-of-vocab cases where TinyLlama collapsed to pose/lean_left.  The
one miss ("tell me a joke" -> stop) is an acceptable failure mode for a robot
daemon: "stop" is a safe no-op.

Wall-clock: Gemma is slower per phrase (~25-60 s, 1-3 t/s generation) than
TinyLlama (~20-28 s).  The banner + model load (~15-20 s) dominates; a
persistent llama-server would amortize this but is out of scope here.

---- parse_intent.py changes ----

Added --model {tinyllama,gemma} flag.  TinyLlama remains the default.
Gemma uses n_predict=64 (vs TinyLlama's 32) because the Gemma chat template
wraps the prompt and the model occasionally burns a few tokens before the
constrained JSON starts.  Both models use the same -st flag set.

  $ ANDROID_SERIAL=9WV4C18C11005454 python3 demo/parse_intent.py --model gemma "jump"
  {"c":"jump"}
  $ ANDROID_SERIAL=9WV4C18C11005454 python3 demo/parse_intent.py "walk forward"
  {"c":"walk","on":true,"stride":150,"step":400}

